english:
  title: A Dedicatory Offering Upon the Completion of the Stupa and the Enshrinement of the Master's Remains
  author: Seokcheon'in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, how sorrowful. Knowledge does not necessarily bear fruit in action. One who cultivates the self does not necessarily benefit others. One who begins well does not necessarily end well. Yet the Great Master, being complete in all three virtues, received the mandate of heaven to establish his lineage and illuminate the world.

    In the Master's own practice, understanding becomes the eye and action becomes the feet. Virtue adorns his countenance and the Way beautifies his form. Whether disparaged or praised, he remains unchanged—his self-knowledge is luminous and his faith in the Way is steadfast.

    When the Master transforms all beings, a clear wind sweeps forth and sweet dew falls gently. The crooked are straightened, the wayward turn to order. An entire realm reveres him as teacher; all sentient beings gather in devotion. In his coming, he discerns the moment and the Great Transformation flows abundantly. In his going, he knows the time and departs in serene liberation. His brightness surpasses the sun and moon; his merit towers above the mountains. Thus he unified knowledge and action, benefited both self and other, and perfected beginning and end alike.

    I, his disciple, reflect upon those days of old. What fortunate karma brought me to encounter our Great Master? What blessing that I heard his dharma! I received the deep grace of his dharma-milk and bore the weighty trust of the dharma-king. My gratitude knows no bounds. Yet by nature I am withdrawn and fond of solitude. Though I attended upon him morning and evening, my service was imperfect. In middle years, occupied with various duties, I often wandered away. When lectures were held through winter and summer, I lacked leisure to serve him with devoted study. I thought: "Our teacher, though aged, remains vigorous. Four or five years hence should bring no grave concern." Had I known his departure would come so swiftly, could I have ever strayed from his side? I do not deny understanding that the world and beyond, the dwelling-place of dharma and its station, are but manifestations of the one nature arising again and again—such is the eternal way. Yet my time of service has been but brief, and now the great season approaches. I have betrayed the dharma's grace. What good is repentance now?

    In the western quarter of our temple, by the left slope of Little Peak, I have found a suitable plot of earth to enshrine the Master's sacred remains. On an auspicious day, I directed the workers to gather stones from distant mountains and fashion them with care. We laid the foundation, raised the stupa—circular within to reflect heaven, square without to reflect earth, with a pointed crown and broad base, embodying the form of all beings. Following ancient custom in every measure, we sealed it and marked it well. And thus, in reverence, we make this offering.

    My only regret is that my means are meager and external support has been wanting. For a full year these remains lay in our humble hermitage. Now, at this solemn rite, I present what little I can offer. I humbly beseech the Master's compassionate acceptance of this sincere devotion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three virtues' refer to knowledge, practice for oneself, and completion—the integrated qualities that distinguish a true master.
  - key: ''
    value: The stupa structure described—circular inside, square outside—symbolizes the harmony between heaven and earth, a common Buddhist architectural principle.
  - key: ''
    value: The Master's departure reflects Buddhist teachings on the impermanence of all conditioned things and the liberation that comes through understanding this truth.
